04628nam a22005895i 9780822380597DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20012001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223805977 a10.1515/97808223805972doi  a(DE-B1597)553938  a(OCoLC)841913044  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF1409.9b.M67 2001eb 7aEDU0070002bisacsh04a980/.71/12211 aMoreiras, Alberto, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Exhaustion of Difference :bThe Politics of Latin American Cultural Studies /cAlberto Moreiras; Fredric Jameson, Stanley Fish. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Conditions of Latin Americanist Critique -- t1. Global Fragments -- t2. Negative Globality and Critical Regionalism -- t3. Theoretical Fictions and Fatal Conceits -- t4. Restitution and Appropriation -- t5. The National Popular in Antonio Candido and Jorge Luis Borges -- t6. The End of Magical Realism: José María Arguedas's Passionate Signifier -- t7. The Aura of Testimonio -- t8. The Order of Order: On the Reluctant Culturalism of Anti-Subalternist Critiques -- t9. Hybridity and Double Consciousness -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe conditions for thinking about Latin America as a regional unit in transnational academic discourse have shifted over the past decades. In The Exhaustion of Difference Alberto Moreiras ponders the ramifications of this shift and draws on deconstruction, Marxian theory, philosophy, political economy, subaltern studies, literary criticism, and postcolonial studies to interrogate the minimal conditions for an effective critique of knowledge given the recent transformations of the contemporary world.What, asks Moreiras, is the function of critical reason in the present moment? What is regionalistic knowledge in the face of globalization? Can regionalistic knowledge be an effective tool for a critique of contemporary reason? What is the specificity of Latin Americanist reflection and how is it situated to deal with these questions? Through examinations of critical regionalism, restitutional excess, the historical genealogy of Latin American subalternism, testimonio literature, and the cultural politics of magical realism, Moreiras argues that while cultural studies is increasingly institutionalized and in danger of reproducing the dominant ideologies of late capitalism, it is also ripe for giving way to projects of theoretical reformulation. Ultimately, he claims, critical reason must abandon its allegiance to aesthetic-historicist projects and the destructive binaries upon which all cultural theories of modernity have been constructed. The Exhaustion of Difference makes a significant contribution to the rethinking of Latin American cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCriticism (Philosophy). 0aLatin American literaturexStudy and teaching (Higher). 0aLatin AmericanistszUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / Curricula.2bisacsh1 aFish, Stanley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822380597zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822380597423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822380597.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  a